TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Group Preference Axiomatization with Cardinal Utility
AU  - Keeney, Ralph L.
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.23.2.140
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.23.2.140
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 140
EP  - 145
VL  - 23
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Given a group composed of N individuals and given that each has rated all of the alternatives using a cardinal utility function, the problem is to aggregate these to obtain a group cardinal utility function for evaluating each alternative. The cardinal utilities indicate the strength of preference of one alternative relative to others as well as order the alternatives. Five assumptions, which seem reasonable for the aggregation, are postulated, and it is shown the group cardinal utility function which is implied must be a linear combination of the individual cardinal utility functions. For assessing such a function, interpersonal comparisons of preferences are required. Suggestions for who should make these comparisons and how they might be done are given.
AB  - Given a group composed of N individuals and given that each has rated all of the alternatives using a cardinal utility function, the problem is to aggregate these to obtain a group cardinal utility function for evaluating each alternative. The cardinal utilities indicate the strength of preference of one alternative relative to others as well as order the alternatives. Five assumptions, which seem reasonable for the aggregation, are postulated, and it is shown the group cardinal utility function which is implied must be a linear combination of the individual cardinal utility functions. For assessing such a function, interpersonal comparisons of preferences are required. Suggestions for who should make these comparisons and how they might be done are given.
